sold%20military%20secrets%20to%20the%20Germans.%20The%20French%20public%20was%20bitterly%20divided%20on%20the%20issue.%20A%20number%20of%20anti-Semitic%20organisations%2C%20for%20example%2C%20the%20newspaper%20%3Cem%3ELa%20Libre%20Parole%3C%2Fem%3E%20edited%20by%20Edouard%20Drumont%2C%20began%20to%20tom-tom%20the%20disloyalty%20of%20French%20Jews.%20Some%20efforts%20were%20made%20to%20defend%20Dreyfuss.%20The%20evidence%20against%20Dreyfuss%20was%20scanty%20and%20increasingly%20the%20scale%20began%20to%20tilt%20towards%20another%20French%20officer%20Fredinand%20Walsin%20Esterhazy.%20He%20was%20however%20acquitted%20of%20treason%20in%20a%20court-martial.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EThe%20injustice%20was%20so%20palpable%2C%20the%20racism%20so%20stark%2C%20and%20public%20prejudice%20so%20unmistakeable%20that%20intellectuals%20could%20no%20longer%20confine%20themselves%20to%20their%20respective%20ivory-towers.%20The%20distinguished%20novelist%20Emile%20Zola%20wrote%20a%20letter%20titled%20J%E2%80%99Accuse%20published%20in%20Clemenceau%E2%80%99s%20newspaper%20%3Cem%3EL%E2%80%99Aurore%3C%2Fem%3E.%20He%20attacked%20the%20army%20for%20covering%20up%20the%20mistaken%20conviction%20of%20Dreyfuss.%20This%20set%20off%20another%20storm%20with%20the%20anti-Dreyfussards%2C%20who%20were%20against%20the%20reopening%20of%20the%20case%2C%20viewing%20support%20for%20Zola%20as%20an%20attempt%20to%20discredit%20the%20army%20and%20weaken%20the%20nation.%20The%20pro-Dreyfussards%20saw%20the%20issue%20in%20wider%20terms%20of%20justice%3A%20the%20defence%20of%20individual%20freedom%20against%20the%20combustible%20rhetoric%20of%20national%20security.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cdiv%20class%3D%5C%22wp-caption%5C%22%3E%3Cimg%20sizes%3D%5C%22(max-width%3A%20709px)%2085vw%2C%20(max-width%3A%20909px)%2067vw%2C%20(max-width%3A%201362px)%2062vw%2C%20840px%5C%22%20src%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fcdn.thewire.in%2Fwp-content%2Fuploads%2F2024%2F03%2F08185210%2FAlfred_Dreyfus_1859-1935.jpg%5C%22%20alt%3D%5C%22%5C%22%20width%3D%5C%22914%5C%22%20srcset%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fcdn.thewire.in%2Fwp-content%2Fuploads%2F2024%2F03%2F08185210%2FAlfred_Dreyfus_1859-1935.jpg%20914w%2C%20https%3A%2F%2Fcdn.thewire.in%2Fwp-content%2Fuploads%2F2024%2F03%2F08185210%2FAlfred_Dreyfus_1859-1935-229x300.jpg%20229w%2C%20https%3A%2F%2Fcdn.thewire.in%2Fwp-content%2Fuploads%2F2024%2F03%2F08185210%2FAlfred_Dreyfus_1859-1935-780x1024.jpg%20780w%5C%22%20class%3D%5C%22wp-image-700835%5C%22%20height%3D%5C%221200%5C%22%3E%3Cp%20class%3D%5C%22wp-caption-text%5C%22%3EAlfred%20Dreyfus.%20Photo%3A%20Wikimedia%20Commons%2FAron%20Gerschel%3C%2Fp%3E%3C%2Fdiv%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EIn%20August%201898%20the%20document%20incriminating%20Dreyfuss%20was%20found%20to%20be%20a%20forgery.%20But%20the%20damage%20had%20been%20done.%20The%20rabid%20right%20had%20come%20into%20the%20political%20limelight.%20The%20philosopher%20Hannah%20Arendt%20believed%20that%20the%20anti-semitic%20movement%20began%20with%20the%20Dreyfuss%20affair.%20Interestingly%2C%20however%2C%20the%20affair%20generated%20the%20acclaimed%20French%20tradition%20of%20%E2%80%98intellectual%20engage%E2%80%99.%20The%20right-wing%20used%20the%20term%20%E2%80%98intellectual%E2%80%99%20with%20contempt%3B%20for%20them%20intellectuals%20were%20anti-national.%20They%20continue%20to%20be%20so%20in%20today%E2%80%99s%20India.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EDespite%20attacks%2C%20French%20society%20continued%20to%20believe%20that%20the%20intellectual%20had%20to%20engage%20with%20injustice%2C%20arbitrary%20state%20power%2C%20threats%20to%20individual%20liberty%2C%20and%20racism.%20When%20the%20philosopher%20and%20writer%20Jean%20Paul%20Sartre%2C%20admired%20and%20loved%20as%20a%20public%20intellectual%2C%20died%20in%201980%2C%20reportedly%2050%2C000%20people%20attended%20his%20funeral.%20Sartre%20had%20argued%20that%20the%20intellectual%20had%20no%20right%20to%20be%20at%20a%20distance%20from%20controversy.%20S%2Fhe%20simply%20did%20not%20have%20the%20privilege%20of%20being%20detached.%20S%2Fhe%20had%20to%20abandon%20self-reflection%20in%20the%20environs%20of%20the%20university%2C%20and%20take%20hold%20of%20the%20era%20to%20change%20society.%20There%20could%20be%20no%20private%20life%20of%20the%20mind%20in%20abstraction%20from%20social%20and%20political%20issues%20and%20struggles.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EIn%201935%2C%20French%20intellectuals%20organised%20an%20International%20Writers%20Assosciation%20for%20the%20Defense%20of%20Culture%20in%20Paris.%20The%20conference%20launched%20the%20largest%20mobilisation%20against%20the%20rise%20of%20fascism%2C%20the%20harbinger%20of%20brutal%20regimes%20in%20the%20world.%20Held%20in%20June%20at%20the%20Palais%20de%20Mutualite%2C%20the%20conference%20was%20attended%20by%20hundreds%20of%20writers.%20Sajjad%20Zaheer%20and%20Mulk%20Raj%20Anand%2C%20who%20were%20to%20play%20a%20major%20role%20in%20turning%20the%20course%20of%20literature%20and%20Urdu%20poetry%20in%20India%2C%20participated%20in%20the%20conference%2C%20along%20with%20Aldous%20Huxley%2C%20EM%20Forster%2C%20Boris%20Pasternak%2C%20Bertold%20Brecht%20and%20Henreich%20Mann.%20The%20controversies%20that%20erupted%20during%20the%20proceedings%20spilled%20over%20into%20the%20streets%20of%20Paris.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3ESocialist%20realism%20held%20the%20day.%20Ilya%20Ehrenburg%2C%20the%20Soviet%20historian%2C%20journalist%20and%20writer%2C%20declared%20that%20any%20form%20of%20art%2C%20which%20was%20not%20a%20weapon%20against%20the%20exploiter%2C%20was%20nothing%20but%20a%20useless%20knick-knack.%20He%20was%20attacked%20by%20Andre%20Breton%2C%20the%20French%20surrealist%20writer%20and%20poet.%20Ultimately%20the%20Congress%20could%20not%20create%20a%20coalition%20of%20anti-fascists%20despite%20individual%20commitment%20to%20the%20cause.%20Shades%20of%20the%20Soviet%20Union%20experiment%20in%20conceptualising%20culture%20instrumentally%20hung%20heavily%20over%20the%20heads%20of%20the%20participants.%20All%20of%20them%20hated%20fascism%2C%20but%20they%20could%20not%20agree%20on%20the%20desirability%20of%20the%20Soviet%20model.%20Reportedly%20the%20surrealist%20Rene%20Crevel%20tried%20to%20mediate%20between%20the%20Surrealists%20and%20Communists%20but%20failed.%20In%20despair%2C%20he%20returned%20to%20his%20apartment%20and%20commited%20suicide%20by%20turning%20the%20gas%20on.%20He%20left%20a%20note%20pinned%20onto%20his%20lapel%20that%20read%20%E2%80%93%20%E2%80%98disgust.%E2%80%99%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3ESome%20great%20debates%20on%20the%20social%20responsibilities%20of%20writers%20and%20poets%20were%20taking%20place%20in%20India%20at%20that%20very%20time.%20The%20belief%20that%20poets%20and%20writers%20have%20to%20take%20poetry%20beyond%20the%20realm%20of%20their%20personal%20pleasures%2C%20desires%2C%20passions%20and%20frustration%20in%20order%20to%20connect%20with%20others%20led%20to%20the%20formation%20of%20the%20Progressive%20Writers%20Association%20in%201936.%20The%20PWA%20notably%20shifted%20the%20political%20discourse%20of%20the%201930s%20away%20from%20competitive%20religious%20nationalism%20to%20poverty%2C%20discrimination%2C%20class%20and%20the%20responsibility%20of%20the%20poet%20in%20a%20crisis-ridden%20society.%20Though%20the%20organisation%20was%20a%20product%20of%2C%20and%20embedded%20in%20the%20national%20movement%20and%20particularly%20the%20politics%20of%20the%20Communist%20Party%20of%20India%2C%20it%20prised%20open%20the%20binary%20opposition%20between%20colonialism%20and%20imperialism%2C%20and%20brought%20in%20another%20dimension%2C%20inequality%2C%20oppression%2C%20and%20patriarchy.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cdiv%20class%3D%5C%22wp-caption%5C%22%3E%3Cimg%20sizes%3D%5C%22(max-width%3A%20709px)%2085vw%2C%20(max-width%3A%20909px)%2067vw%2C%20(max-width%3A%201362px)%2062vw%2C%20840px%5C%22%20src%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fcdn.thewire.in%2Fwp-content%2Fuploads%2F2022%2F05%2F22132503%2FFS1.png%5C%22%20alt%3D%5C%22%5C%22%20width%3D%5C%22866%5C%22%20srcset%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fcdn.thewire.in%2Fwp-content%2Fuploads%2F2022%2F05%2F22132503%2FFS1.png%20866w%2C%20https%3A%2F%2Fcdn.thewire.in%2Fwp-content%2Fuploads%2F2022%2F05%2F22132503%2FFS1-300x183.png%20300w%5C%22%20class%3D%5C%22wp-image-597781%5C%22%20height%3D%5C%22527%5C%22%3E%3Cp%20class%3D%5C%22wp-caption-text%5C%22%3EProgressive%20Writers%20in%20Bombay%2C%201946%3A%20Sultana%20Jafri%2C%20Ismat%20Chugtai%2C%20Vishwamitra%20Adil%2C%20Ali%20Sardar%20Jafri%2C%20Krishan%20Chander%2C%20Mahendranath%2C%20Mumtaz%20Hussain%2C%20Rajinder%20Singh%20Bedi%2C%20Sahir%20Ludhianvi%20and%20Habib%20Tanvir.%20Picture%20courtesy%3A%20India-Pak%20Heritage%20groupht%3C%2Fp%3E%3C%2Fdiv%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EAt%20the%20first%20meeting%20in%201936%2C%20Sajjad%20Zaheer%20reiterated%20that%20it%20is%20the%20duty%20of%20the%20writer%20to%20struggle%20against%20reaction%20and%20ignorance%20in%20whatever%20form%20they%20manifest%20themselves%20in%20society.%20Mulk%20Raj%20Anand%20reiterated%20that%20the%20goal%20of%20the%20PWA%20was%20to%20liberate%20Indian%20society%20from%20maligning%20imperialist%20archeology%20and%20from%20its%20misuse%20by%20reactionary%20elements%20in%20our%20society-narrow%20nationalist%20revivalists%2C%20the%20priest-craft%20and%20orthodoxy.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EThe%20social%20function%20of%20poetry%20was%20ably%20summed%20up%20by%20India%E2%80%99s%20leading%20poet%20Sahir%20Ludhianvi.%20The%20job%20of%20the%20poet%20is%20incomplete%20if%20it%20does%20not%20reach%20the%20poor-%E2%80%98%3Cem%3EPhan%20jo%20naadar%20tak%20nahin%20pahuncha%2Fapne%20meyaar%20tak%20nahin%20pahuncha%3C%2Fem%3E%E2%80%99.%20For%20this%20we%20need%20a%20different%20gaze%2C%20not%20one%20that%20is%20obsessed%20with%20our%20pains%20and%20pleasures%20but%20one%20that%20connects%20with%20our%20fellow%20beings%2C%20with%20suffering%2C%20and%20which%20creates%20empathy%20through%20solidarity.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EThe%20manifesto%20read%3A%20%E2%80%9CRadical%20changes%20are%20taking%20place%20in%20Indian%20society%E2%80%A6We%20believe%20that%20the%20new%20literature%20of%20India%20must%20deal%20with%20the%20basic%20problems%20of%20existence%20today%20%E2%80%93the%20problem%20of%20hunger%20and%20poverty%2C%20social%20backwardness%2C%20and%20political%20subjection.%20All%20that%20drags%20us%20down%20to%20passivity%2C%20inaction%2C%20and%20un-reason%20we%20reject%20as%20reactionary.%20All%20that%20arouses%20in%20us%20the%20critical%20spirit%2C%20which%20examines%20institutions%20and%20customs%20in%20the%20light%20of%20reason%2C%20which%20helps%20us%20to%20act%2C%20to%20organise%20ourselves%2C%20to%20transform%2C%20we%20accept%20as%20progressive%E2%80%9D.%20Social%20realism%20replaced%20romanticism%2C%20as%20well%20as%20the%20idea%20that%20the%20poet%2Fwriter%20was%20above%20politics.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3ELike%20all%20radical%20movements%2C%20the%20PWA%20was%20internationalist%20in%20its%20vision.%20Two%20of%20the%20organisers%20Sajjad%20Zaheer%20and%20Mulk%20Raj%20Anand%20had%20been%20associated%20with%20the%20Bloombury%20group%20in%20London.%20The%20writer%20Leonard%20Wolfe%20along%20with%20his%20wife%20Virginia%2C%20Virginia%E2%80%99s%20sister%20Vanessa%20Bell%20and%20a%20group%20of%20friends%20from%20Cambridge%2C%20established%20the%20Bloomsbury%20group%20as%20the%20centre%20of%20a%20new%20aesthetic%20and%20intellectual%20culture.%20The%20idea%20was%20to%20break%20with%20old%20social%20mores%2C%20discover%20new%20modes%20of%20defying%20borders%20of%20art%20and%20culture%2C%20and%20invent%20new%20notions%20of%20personal%20intimacy.%20The%20group%20inspired%20a%20new%20aesthetic.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EMulk%20Raj%20Anand%20(1905)%2C%20eminent%20novelist%2C%20essayist%2C%20and%20critic%2C%20attended%20the%20meetings%20of%20the%20group%20to%20which%20he%20was%20invited%20by%20Leonard%20Wolfe%20and%20E.M%20Forster.%20Forster%20wrote%20the%20preface%20to%20%3Cem%3EUntouchable%3C%2Fem%3E.%20Anand%E2%80%99s%20%3Cem%3ELetters%20on%20India%3C%2Fem%3E%20carried%20a%20foreword%20by%20Leonard%20Woolf.%20And%20his%20other%20works%20were%20well%20reviewed%20by%20Bonamy%20Dovree%2C%20Stephen%20Spender%2C%20and%20George%20Orwell.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EAnand%20returned%20to%20India%20in%201945%2C%20and%20in%201981%2C%20he%20wrote%20%3Cem%3EConversations%20in%20Bloomsbury%3C%2Fem%3E.%20He%20was%20attracted%20by%20learned%20discussions%20but%20the%20group%20dissatisfied%20him.%20In%20the%20preface%20to%20the%20second%20edition%20of%20the%20book%20published%20in%201995%2C%20Anand%20wrote%20that%20most%20of%20the%20intellectuals%20who%20gathered%20for%20informal%20evenings%20at%20Virginia%20Woolf%E2%80%99s%20residence%20in%20Tavistock%20Place%20almost%20deliberately%20avoided%20talking%20about%20politics.%20This%20made%20him%20nervous.%20%E2%80%9CThe%20writers%20of%20the%20Bloomsbury%20Group%2C%20and%20their%20affiliates%20in%20the%20Universities%20of%20Oxford%20and%20Cambride%20were%2C%20of%20course%2C%20humane%20people%2C%20but%20like%20the%20exalted%20Mayfair-Kensington-Bayswater-Wimbledon-Kew%20Gardens%20middle%20sections%2C%20they%20remained%20enclosed%20in%20their%20precious%20worlds%2C%20without%20guilts%20about%20their%20status%20as%20aristocrats%20having%20been%20achieved%20by%20the%20labour%20of%20generations%20of%20industrial%20workers%20in%20Midlands%20and%20the%20colonies.%E2%80%9D%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EHe%20was%20upset%20by%20their%20refusal%20to%20participate%20in%20politics%2C%20even%20as%20Hitler%20and%20Mussolini%E2%80%99s%20ignoble%20politics%20confronted%20them%20in%20newspapers.%20When%20Mussolini%20wantonly%20attacked%20and%20occupied%20Ethiopia%2C%20wrote%20Anand%2C%20they%20saw%20it%20as%20a%20tragic%20joke%20that%20this%20Italian%20was%20reviving%20Ceasarism.%20Hitler%E2%80%99s%20occupation%20of%20Austria%20brought%20frowns.%20When%20Prime%20Minister%20Neville%20Chamberlain%20signed%20the%20Munich%20Pact%20and%20conceded%20Sudentanland%20to%20Hitler%2C%20they%20seemed%20to%20be%20taken%20in%20by%20the%20promise%20of%20peace%20in%20our%20time.%20When%20the%20young%20sons%20of%20big%20houses%20Stephen%20Spender%2C%20W.H%20Auden%2C%20Cecil%20Day%2C%20Edward%20Upward%2C%20Louis%20Macniece%20began%20to%20march%20in%20anti-Fascist%20protest%20processions%20in%20the%20streets%2C%20Virigina%20Woolf%20dubbed%20them%20as%20the%20%E2%80%98Leaning%20Tower%E2%80%99%20School%20of%20Poets.%20A%20number%20of%20critics%20including%20Raymond%20Williams%20characterised%20the%20group%20as%20upper-class%20and%20generally%20dismissive%20of%20the%20working%20class%2C%20of%20people%20who%20upheld%20imperialism%2C%20and%20who%20had%20no%20time%20for%20the%20freedom%20movement.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EAnand%20was%20fascinated%20by%20the%20exciting%20ideas%20voiced%20in%20Bloomsbury%2C%20but%20uncomfortable%20about%20the%20unspoken%20ban%20on%20political%20stands.%20Indians%2C%20he%20wrote%2C%20had%20seen%20the%20ugly%20face%20of%20fascism%20before%20the%20Europeans%20saw%20it.%20He%20wanted%20to%20create%20an%20intellectual%20space%20which%20had%20the%20intellectual%20exuberance%20of%20Bloomsbury%2C%20but%20which%20was%20political%20and%20anti-imperialist.%20What%20he%20did%20learn%20from%20the%20group%20was%20the%20significance%20of%20culture%20as%20a%20political%20intervention.%20The%20public%20intellectual%20could%20not%20be%20above%20politics%20or%20part%20of%20the%20ruling%20elite.%20S%2Fhe%20had%20to%20create%20a%20new%20vision%20that%20would%20inspire%20an%20India%20caught%20up%20in%20the%20pettiness%20of%20religious%20politics%2C%20and%20heedless%20of%20the%20misery%20which%20befell%20millions%20of%20its%20countrymen.%20This%20is%20our%20crying%20need%20even%20today.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EThis%20is%20not%20to%20suggest%20that%20the%20PWA%20was%20not%20marked%20by%20profound%20tensions%20between%20members%20of%20the%20Communist%20Party%20and%20those%20who%20preferred%20heterogeneity%2C%20between%20defenders%20of%20style%20and%20those%20of%20substance%2C%20and%20on%20the%20issue%20of%20the%20relationship%20between%20a%20new%20ethics%20and%20literature.%20The%20members%20knew%20that%20the%20term%20progressive%20was%20neither%20a%20given%20nor%20self-explanatory.%20It%20was%20a%20matter%20for%20debate.%20What%20they%20shared%20was%20the%20conviction%20that%20literature%20had%20to%20socially%20revitalise%20a%20society%2C%20raise%20questions%20about%20who%20we%20are%20and%20what%20we%20want%20to%20be%2C%20and%20indicate%20the%20road%20from%20what%20is%2C%20to%20what%20can%20be.%20This%20was%20emphasised%20by%20Munshi%20Premchand%20in%20his%20inaugural%20address%20at%20the%20first%20meeting.%20Literature%20must%20engage%20with%20our%20sense%20of%20beauty%2C%20and%20on%20the%20other%20face%20the%20grim%20realities%20of%20life%20with%20determination.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EMost%20of%20progressive%20poetry%20is%20concerned%20with%20arousing%20indignation%20and%20anger%20at%20the%20sheer%20desolation%20of%20life%20lived%20by%20millions%2C%20and%20is%20concerned%20with%20taking%20us%20beyond%20the%20realm%20of%20our%20personal%20lives%20to%20the%20lives%20of%20others.%20This%20is%20the%20tradition%20of%20the%20Progressive%20Writers%20Association%20and%20social%20realism.%20Sajjad%20Zaheer%20remarked%20that%20though%20the%20ghazal%20was%20still%20attractive%2C%20fervor%20was%20created%20in%20a%20mushaira%20only%20when%20the%20poet%20attacked%20the%20oppressor%2C%20exposed%20hypocrisy%2C%20described%20the%20real%20condition%20of%20the%20masses%2C%20delivered%20a%20message%20of%20unity%2C%20action%2C%20and%20struggle%20and%20predicted%20a%20future%20of%20freedom%20and%20justice.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EPoets%20%E2%80%93%20Majaz%2C%20Kaifi%20Azmi%2C%20Sahir%2C%20Faiz%2C%20Makhdoon%20Moinuddin%2C%20Amrita%20Pritam%2C%20Rajendra%20Singh%20Bedi%2C%20and%20Ali%20Sardar%20Jafri%20began%20%E2%80%93%20to%20write%20of%20gham-e-dauran%20or%20the%20material%20world%20instead%20of%20gham-e-jaana.%20Most%20poets%20did%20both.%20Kaifi%20Azmi%20who%20wrote%20one%20of%20the%20most%20acclaimed%20love%20sonnets%20for%20Chetan%20Anand%E2%80%99s%20Heer%20Ranjha-%E2%80%98%3Cem%3Emeri%20duniya%20mein%20tum%20aaye%20kya%20kya%20apne%20saath%20liye%3C%2Fem%3E%E2%80%99%2C%20also%20famously%20wrote%20%E2%80%98%3Cem%3EUth%20Meri%20Jaan.%20Mere%20Saath%20Hi%20Chalna%20Hai%20Tujeh%3C%2Fem%3E%E2%80%99.%C2%A0%20Sahir%20could%20write%20a%20bhangra%20number%20for%20Kabhi%20Kabhi%2C%20but%20also%20write%20%3Cem%3E%E2%80%98kahan%20hai%2C%20kahan%20hai%20muhafiz%20khudi%20ke%3C%2Fem%3E%E2%80%99.%20Majrooh%20Sultanpuri%20wrote%20beautiful%20lyrics%2C%20but%20also%20used%20the%20ghazal%20to%20transform%20the%20idea%20of%20beauty.%20Beauty%20was%20in%20the%20body%20of%20the%20toiler%2C%20the%20mehnat-kash%20insaan%20%E2%80%93%E2%80%98surkh%20inquilab%20aaya%2C%20daur-e-aftaab%20aaya%2FMuntazir%20thi%20yeh%20aakehn%20jis%20ki%20ek%20zamane%20se%2FAb%20zameen%20gayagi%2C%20hal%20ke%20saaz%20pe%20nagme%E2%80%A6.Ab%20sanwar%20ke%20niklega%2C%20husn%20kaarkhane%20se%E2%80%99.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EAfter%20independence%2C%20the%20PWA%20declined%20for%20a%20variety%20of%20reasons%2C%20but%20a%20number%20of%20poets%20continued%20to%20suggest%2C%20against%20prevailing%20sentiments%2C%20that%20India%20and%20Pakistan%20should%20live%20in%20harmony.%20Going%20against%20the%20rabid%20nationalism%20which%20marked%20the%201965%20war%20with%20Pakistan%2C%20Ali%20Sardar%20Jafri%20wrote%20%E2%80%98%3Cem%3EVoh%20din%20aaye%20ke%20aansoo%20ho%20ke%20nafrat%20dil%20se%20beh%20jaaye%2FVoh%20din%20aaye%20ye%20sarhad%20bosa-e-lab%20ban%20kar%20reh%20jaaye%3C%2Fem%3E%E2%80%99.%20And%20his%20famous%20verse%20from%20%E2%80%98%3Cem%3EKaun%20dushman%20hain%3C%2Fem%3E%3F%E2%80%99%20in%20the%20same%20period%20resounded%20with%20these%20words%20%E2%80%98%3Cem%3ETum%20aao%20gulshan-e-Lahore%20se%20chaman%20bar-dosh%20se%2FHum%20aayen%20subh-e-Banaras%20ki%20raushni%20lekar%2FHimaalaya%20ki%20havaaon%20ki%20taazagi%20lekar%2FPhir%20us%20ke%20baad%20yeh%20poochenge%2C%20kaun%20dushman%20hai.%3C%2Fem%3E%E2%80%99%20And%20above%20all%2C%20there%20is%20Gulzar%20who%20wrote%20with%20some%20poignancy%3A%20%E2%80%9C%3Cem%3ETumhe%20aziz%20hai%20apna%20watan%2Fmain%20jaanta%20hoon%2Fmujhe%20bhi%20us%20se%20mohabbat%20hai%2Ftum%20yakeen%20kar%20lo%2Fzara%20sa%20pharak%20hai%20gar%20tum%20samajh%20sako%20isko%2Fki%20tum%20wahin%20ke%20ho%20aur%20main%20wahin%20se%20hoon%E2%80%9D%3C%2Fem%3E.%20As%20a%20voice%20that%20suggests%20alternatives%20to%20dominant%20ideologies%2C%20the%20poet%20invokes%20imaginations%20of%20what%20could%20be.%20We%20do%20not%20have%20to%20live%20with%20hate.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3ESignificantly%20poets%20despaired%20of%20the%20inability%20of%20the%20post-independence%20government%20to%20resolve%20issues%20of%20poverty%20and%20class%2C%20inequality%20and%20oppression.%20Sahir%E2%80%99s%20was%20direct%20about%20the%20need%20to%20mobilise%20people%20against%20oppression%20and%20subordination.%20%E2%80%98%3Cem%3EChaalo%20ki%20aak%20sabhi%20paymaal%20roohon%20se%2F%20Kahen%20ke%20apne%20hare%20k%20zakhm%20ko%20zubaan%20kar%20de%2F%20Hamara%20raaz%20hamara%20nahin%2C%20sabhi%20ka%20hai%2FChalon%20ke%20sare%20zamane%20ko%20raazdan%20kar%20de%3C%2Fem%3E%E2%80%99%20Kaifi%20Azmi%20was%20direct%20in%20his%20call%20for%20revolution%3A%20%E2%80%98%3Cem%3EKahaan%20tak%20ye%20bil-jabr%20mar%20mar%20ke%20jeena%2F%20Badalne%20laga%20hai%20amal%20ka%20qareena.%20Lahu%20mein%20hai%20khaulan%2C%20jabeen%20par%20paseena%2C%20Dhadakti%20hai%20nasben%2C%20sulagta%20hai%20seena%2FGaraj%20ai%20baghavat%20ke%20tayyaar%20hoon%20main%3C%2Fem%3E.%E2%80%99%E2%80%99%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3ESahir%20was%20the%20conscience%20of%20our%20society%3B%20forthright%20about%20the%20need%20to%20resist%20injustice.%20After%20independence%20when%20right%20winger%20systematically%20set%20about%20suppressing%20Urdu%20as%20the%20language%20of%20the%20minority%2C%20the%20celebrations%20of%20Ghalib%E2%80%99s%20birth%20centenary%20prompted%20Sahir%20to%20write%20in%20an%20ironic%20vein%3A%20%3Cem%3E%E2%80%98Jin%20shahro%20mein%20goonji%20thi%20Ghalib%20ki%20nava%20barson%2FUn%20shahron%20mein%20aaj%20Urdu%20be-naam-o-nishan%20thahri%2FAazadi-e-kaamil%20ka%20ailaan%20hua%20jis%20din%2FMa%E2%80%99atob%20zabaan%20thahri%2C%20ghaddar%20zabaan%20thahri%2F%20Jis%20ahd-e-siyasat%20ne%20ye%20zinda%20zuban%20kuchli%2FUs%20ahd-e-siyasat%20ko%20marhoomofi%20ka%20gham%20kyu%20hai%2FGhalib%20jise%20kehte%20hain%20Urdu%20hi%20ka%20shayar%20tha%2FUrdu%20pe%20sitam%20dha%20kar%2C%20Ghalib%20pe%20karam%20kyu%20hain%E2%80%99.%3C%2Fem%3E%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EThe%20progressive%20poet%20is%20the%20conscience%20of%20humankind%2C%20the%20quintessential%20public%20intellectual.%20We%20need%20them%20even%20more%20today%2C%20to%20awaken%20the%20consciousness%20of%20a%20supine%20middle%20class%20which%20has%20ceased%20to%20care%20about%20the%20vulnerable%20and%20the%20exploited.%20The%20public%20intellectual%20does%20not%20have%20to%20be%20a%20poet%2C%20but%20there%20is%20something%20special%20about%20poets%2C%20they%20touch%20our%20souls.%20They%20might%20even%20touch%20the%20soul%20of%20an%20India%20indifferent%20to%20the%20finer%20aspects%20of%20culture%2C%20an%20India%20caught%20up%20once%20again%20in%20the%20pettiness%20of%20religious%20politics.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3E%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fthewire.in%2Fauthor%2Fneera-chandhoke%5C%22%3E%3Ci%3ENeera%20Chandhoke%3C%2Fi%3E%3C%2Fa%3E%3Ci%3E%C2%A0was%20a%20professor%20of%20political%20science%20at%20Delhi%20University.%C2%A0%3C%2Fi%3E%3C%2Fp%3E%22%2C%22published%22%3A1709965760000%2C%22visual%22%3A%22https%3A%2F%2Fcdn.thewire.in%2Fwp-content%2Fuploads%2F2018%2F08%2F22130752%2Ffree-speech-2.jpg%22%2C%22originID%22%3A%22https%3A%2F%2Fthewire.in%2Frights%2Fin-search-of-a-public-intellectual%22%2C%22summary%22%3A%22A%20public%20intellectual%20can%20create%20a%20new%20vision%20that%20would%20inspire%20an%20India%20caught%20up%20in%20the%20pettiness%20of%20religious%20politics%2C%20to%20awaken%20the%20consciousness%20of%20a%20supine%20middle%20class%20which%20has%20ceased%20to%20care%20about%20the%20vulnerable%20and%20exploited.%20This%20is%20our%20crying%20need%20today.%22%